whether the note issue from the Mouth of God or from that hungry infant.

00:27:00,000 --> 00:27:06,500
But where do these notes come from? Why do I ears select certain notes and not others.

00:27:07,000 --> 00:27:13,500
For example, why do children tease one other in a specific sing-song way.

00:27:15,000 --> 00:27:21,500
Two very special notes, which children also use to call one another.

00:27:22,000 --> 00:27:25,500
Jerry, Doris, whatever!

00:27:26,000 --> 00:27:31,500
And which are often used by them in their singing games. Little Sally Water.

00:27:32,000 --> 00:27:36,500
That's the same two notes, only now expanded to three notes.

00:27:37,000 --> 00:27:39,500
Little Sally Water.

00:27:40,000 --> 00:27:44,500
Or perhaps you once yells: Ali Ali Anfery. Does that sound familiar?

00:27:45,000 --> 00:27:50,500
Well, again we must ask why just those notes in that particular order.

00:27:52,000 --> 00:28:01,500
Research seems to indicate that this exact constellation of two notes and its three note variant

00:28:02,000 --> 00:28:09,500
is the same all over the world wherever children tease each other, on every continent and in every culture.

00:28:10,000 --> 00:28:16,500
In short, we may have heard a clear case of a musical linguistic universal,

00:28:17,000 --> 00:28:20,500
and one which can be identified and explained in a none-vacuous way.

00:28:21,000 --> 00:28:29,500
I want to take a little time to do this carefully because in the explanation lies the key to musical universality in general.

00:28:29,580 --> 00:28:33,500
The answer to the question why just those notes,

00:28:33,580 --> 00:28:40,500
and eventually to the question why those notes in Mozart,
and why those notes in Copland, or in SchÃ¶nberg, or whoever.

00:28:40,580 --> 00:28:47,500
And in having an answer, we musicians have a singular advantage over the linguists who ask their question:

00:28:47,800 --> 00:28:51,500
why just those sounds in human speech?

00:28:52,800 --> 00:28:56,500
And they seek the answers by constructing a very complex hypothesis,

00:28:56,800 --> 00:29:00,500
which is still very much in the working stage,

00:29:00,600 --> 00:29:04,500
subject to proof or disproof, amplification or derision.

00:29:05,000 --> 00:29:13,500
But we musicians are luckier; we have the built-in, pre-ordained, universal, known as the harmonic series.

00:29:13,600 --> 00:29:18,500
To those of you who know all about the harmonic series, I beg your indulgence for a few minutes,

00:29:19,000 --> 00:29:22,500
so that I can sketch it out for those who don't.

00:29:23,000 --> 00:29:28,500
This accoutic phenomenon, called the harmonic series or overtone series,

00:29:28,580 --> 00:29:33,500
is not hard to understand, if you remember the basic high school fact:

00:29:33,580 --> 00:29:38,500
that all sounds are produced by vibrating bodies, which send out waves.

00:29:39,000 --> 00:29:47,500
If such a vibrating body is irregularly constituted like this floor, or this piano,

00:29:48,000 --> 00:29:55,500
it will emit waves which are irregular, and our ears will perceive them as noise
(Ou..)

00:29:56,000 --> 00:30:03,500
But if the source of vibration is of a consistent structure, like anyone of the strings in this piano,

00:30:04,000 --> 00:30:10,500
it will emit regular waves and we hear them as a musical tone.

00:30:11,000 --> 00:30:16,500
Of course the source does not have to be a string, it can be a column of air as in a clarinet,

00:30:17,000 --> 00:30:23,500
or a column of steel as in a tubular bell, or a stretched animal hide as in a kettle drum.

00:30:24,000 --> 00:30:30,500
But whatever it is it produces what's called energy in vibratory motion, that is the official language,

00:30:31,000 --> 00:30:37,500
by being beaten, blown, plucked, struck or frictionised with a bow.

00:30:38,000 --> 00:30:41,500
Let's settle for a piano string, let's say this one,

00:30:42,000 --> 00:30:47,500
which is of a particular length, tension, thickness and density.

00:30:48,000 --> 00:30:55,500
and when struck by its hammer produces sound waves of a frequency of 132 vibrations per second,

00:30:56,000 --> 00:30:58,500
and is known to the world as the note C.

00:31:00,000 --> 00:31:05,500
Now comes the interesting part, if I sit at the piano and play that low C,

00:31:06,000 --> 00:31:12,500
you may think you are hearing only that one tone: a dark, rich, base note.

00:31:13,000 --> 00:31:16,500
But you are not, you are simultaneously hearing a whole series of higher tones

00:31:17,000 --> 00:31:19,500
that are sounding at the same time.

00:31:21,000 --> 00:31:29,500
These are arranged in an order preordained by nature and ruled by universal physical laws.

00:31:30,000 --> 00:31:31,500
If this is news to you, I hope it's good news.

00:31:31,600 --> 00:31:35,500
Because all these upper notes of which you may be unaware,

00:31:35,570 --> 00:31:41,500
result from a phenomenon of nature, whereby any sound producing source,

00:31:42,000 --> 00:31:46,500
or shall I say pitch producing source such as this piano string,

00:31:47,000 --> 00:31:54,500
vibrates not only as the whole string in all its whatever inch glory sounding that low C;

00:31:55,000 --> 00:32:00,500
but also in fractional segments of that string, each vibrating separately.

00:32:01,000 --> 00:32:06,500
It's as though the string were infinitely divisable into two halves,

00:32:07,000 --> 00:32:08,500
and into three thirds and four quarters and so on.

00:32:09,000 --> 00:32:13,500
And the smaller those segments are, the faster they vibrate,

00:32:13,600 --> 00:32:19,500
producing higher and higher frequencies, and therefore higher and higher tones,

00:32:19,580 --> 00:32:24,500
overtones; or harmonics, says they are sometimes called.

00:32:25,000 --> 00:32:28,500
And these overtones or harmonics are all sounding together

00:32:29,000 --> 00:32:32,500
with the fundamental sound of the full string;

00:32:32,580 --> 00:32:36,500
this is a basic principle by which the entire harmonic theory is generated.

00:32:37,000 --> 00:32:39,500
starting on any fundamental tone.

00:32:40,000 --> 00:32:43,500
Now if you already knew all that from high school physics,

00:32:43,580 --> 00:32:49,000
you'll also know that these overtones are naturally less apparent to the ear than the fundamental,

00:32:49,200 --> 00:32:51,500
which is in this case low C.

00:32:52,000 --> 00:32:56,500
And in fact they sound more and more faintly as they go higher.

00:32:56,550 --> 00:33:02,500
Any note I strike will contain its own series of overtones.

00:33:02,560 --> 00:33:08,500
But the lower the note I strike, the more abundantly audible will be its homarnic series,

00:33:08,600 --> 00:33:12,500
which accouts in part for the comparative richness of this low C.

00:33:13,000 --> 00:33:18,500
Now remember I spoke of the preordained order in which the overtones appear.

00:33:19,000 --> 00:33:24,500
Let's see if I can make you actually hear those overtones in that order.

00:33:25,000 --> 00:33:28,500
The first overtone of the series according to the laws of physics

00:33:29,000 --> 00:33:34,500
has to be exatly an octive higher than the fundamental C we've been hearing.

00:33:35,000 --> 00:33:39,500
In other words, this got to be this C, an octive higher.

00:33:40,000 --> 00:33:44,500
Now if I silently press down the key of this higher C,

00:33:45,000 --> 00:33:51,500
and hold it so that the string is free to vibrate. And then abruptly strike the fundamental C, an octive lower,

00:33:51,600 --> 00:33:54,500
what do you hear?

00:33:56,000 --> 00:34:01,500
You are clearly hearing the firat overtone vibrating sympathetically an octive above its fundamental.

00:34:02,000 --> 00:34:04,500
I hope you heard it, did you? Listen again.

00:34:07,000 --> 00:34:14,500
Clear as a bell. So obviously this upper C is an integral part of the C an octive below.

00:34:15,000 --> 00:34:21,500
It's a built-in harmonic sounded by the two halves of that lower string vibrating independently.

00:34:22,000 --> 00:34:29,500
Of the next overtone of this preordained order, results from that same fundamental string

00:34:29,700 --> 00:34:32,500
vibrating in three parts;

00:34:33,000 --> 00:34:37,500
and this one will be the first different overtone, that is the first one you will hear other than a C.

00:34:38,000 --> 00:34:40,500
That's going to be a G, this G.

00:34:41,000 --> 00:34:45,500
Now let's repeat our experiment, I press this new one down silently,

00:34:46,700 --> 00:34:48,500
and then again strike this fundamental C.

00:34:50,000 --> 00:34:53,500
What do we hear now? That G, right?

00:34:53,700 --> 00:34:57,500
A new tone, again clear as a bell. You want to hear it again?

00:35:00,000 --> 00:35:03,300
Now we've just reached a very significant point.

00:35:03,500 --> 00:35:07,300
Have you noticed that the fundamental tone and its first overtone

00:35:07,500 --> 00:35:10,500
are really the same note C but an octive apart.

00:35:11,000 --> 00:35:16,500
But this new overtone G is a fifth away from C.

00:35:16,600 --> 00:35:22,300
So we now have two different tones. And once they are established in our ears,

00:35:22,500 --> 00:35:26,500
we are in possession of the key to the whole tonal system,

00:35:27,500 --> 00:35:31,200
a system based on the concept of tonic and dominant.

00:35:31,300 --> 00:35:33,000
Tonic and dominant.

00:35:33,200 --> 00:35:41,500
This C represents the idea of tonic, which has the function of establishing the tonal center of any given key.

00:35:44,000 --> 00:35:50,100
And the function of the dominant, is to aid and abet in the establishment of that tonality,

00:35:50,400 --> 00:35:57,500
through a special relationship it enjoys with the tonic, owing to their proximity in the harmonic series.

00:35:59,000 --> 00:36:01,000
But more of that later.

00:36:01,100 --> 00:36:06,500
Right now onto the next overtone which is again a C,

00:36:07,000 --> 00:36:09,500
a fourth higher than the G we've just heard.

00:36:10,000 --> 00:36:17,500
Shall we repeat the experiment? I press it down silently, there it is, you hear it?

00:36:18,000 --> 00:36:20,500
Shall we do it again?

00:36:21,000 --> 00:36:25,500
Now the next one is again a new pitch.

00:36:25,700 --> 00:36:28,500
This time a third higher than its predecessor.

00:36:29,000 --> 00:36:33,500
Notice that the intervals are getting progessively smaller as we ascend the series,

00:36:33,800 --> 00:36:38,500
began with an octive and then a fifth and then a fourth and then, now, a third.

00:36:38,800 --> 00:36:44,500
And the new overtone will be this note E. Listen.

00:36:47,000 --> 00:36:52,500
It's a bit fainter, but it's there for all to hear. Shall I try it again?

00:36:55,000 --> 00:37:03,500
Hear it way back there? One last time. It's clear.

00:37:04,000 --> 00:37:07,200
And there you have the first four overtones of the series:

00:37:07,300 --> 00:37:14,500
A fundamental plus one two three four, three of which are of different pitches,

00:37:15,000 --> 00:37:22,500
those three. Now it must be obvious to you that these three notes rearranged in scale order,

00:37:23,000 --> 00:37:29,500
constitute what is known as the major triad, which is the very nucleus,

00:37:29,600 --> 00:37:32,100
the cornerstone of most of the music we hear from day to day,

00:37:32,300 --> 00:37:36,500
whether it's a symphony or a hymn, or a blues.

00:37:36,600 --> 00:37:41,200
And this triad with its tonic-dominant relationship,

00:37:41,300 --> 00:37:44,500
plus the third sandwiched between,

00:37:44,600 --> 00:37:50,000
this triad is the fundation of Western tonal music as it developed

00:37:50,100 --> 00:37:55,200
of the last three centuries or so, along with the development of our western culture in general.

00:37:55,300 --> 00:37:59,200
Let's not make the mistake that so many people make

00:37:59,300 --> 00:38:03,200
of regarding this triad as the basic universal.

00:38:03,300 --> 00:38:08,200
That's a miscomprehension that's far too common,

00:38:08,250 --> 00:38:12,200
in that it fails to recognise that our accidental culture is only one of many world's cultures,

00:38:12,250 --> 00:38:16,200
in spite of its current prevalence and its worldwide influence;

00:38:16,311 --> 00:38:20,200
and in spite of the fact that it thinks it's the only important culture.

00:38:20,311 --> 00:38:26,200
A perfect example of this, a fact of this misconception

00:38:26,311 --> 00:38:29,200
arises with the very next overtone in the series,

00:38:29,250 --> 00:38:31,200
which is a stranger to the western tonal culture.

00:38:31,250 --> 00:38:35,200
In fact this next overtone does not even appear on the piano,

00:38:35,250 --> 00:38:39,200
which means I cannot demonstrate it for you as I have for the preceding ones.

00:38:39,411 --> 00:38:45,200
More exactly stated, it is not to be found on the piano in its natural, pure form

00:38:45,411 --> 00:38:49,200
as it derives by physical law from that fundamental C string.

00:38:49,411 --> 00:38:52,200
Let me digress a moment to tell you why.

00:38:52,450 --> 00:38:58,000
You see this piano, like all keyboard instruments, is a tempered instrument

00:38:58,050 --> 00:39:02,100
which means its notes have been tempered or "tampered with"

00:39:02,211 --> 00:39:06,100
(I don't mean a joke by that, just mean to clarify the word).

00:39:06,211 --> 00:39:11,100
So that each one of them, each one of these notes can serve its function in all

00:39:11,150 --> 00:39:14,100
twelve keys at once.

00:39:14,411 --> 00:39:20,100
This readjustment in tuning became inevitable when music reached its tonal adulthood,

00:39:20,411 --> 00:39:24,000
around 1700; and found that it didn't have to remain in one key

00:39:24,005 --> 00:39:27,000
from the beginning to the end of a piece,

00:39:27,205 --> 00:39:30,200
but can modulate from one key to another in the course of it;

00:39:30,205 --> 00:39:34,400
but the notes deriving naturally from the harmonic series

00:39:34,505 --> 00:39:38,400
will work only in one key at a time. Do you follow that?

00:39:38,505 --> 00:39:43,400
One key at a time. That is what in tune in one key

00:39:43,605 --> 00:39:47,400
is likely to be out of tune in another.

00:39:48,000 --> 00:39:55,400
Would you believe that if this piano were to encompass only natural untempered tones,

00:39:55,410 --> 00:39:57,400
this single octive space

00:39:57,410 --> 00:40:02,400
would have to contain 77 different keys?

00:40:02,610 --> 00:40:05,400
Well, you can understand that a compromise has to be made somewhere,

00:40:05,610 --> 00:40:08,400
and that "somewhere" was the moment in history

00:40:08,610 --> 00:40:11,400
when the rapid development of tonal harmony

00:40:11,610 --> 00:40:18,400
coinciding with the equally rapid development of the keyboard instruments with their fixed, unchangeable tones.

00:40:18,610 --> 00:40:22,400
And that is how the tempered clavier chord came to be,

00:40:22,610 --> 00:40:24,400
to say nothing of this Baldwin Grand.

00:40:24,610 --> 00:40:28,400
And that's why I can't play you this next overtone.

00:40:28,610 --> 00:40:32,400
But if we actually approach it pianistically

00:40:32,410 --> 00:40:39,400
in our ascent of the harmonic series, we find it somewhere around here,

00:40:39,500 --> 00:40:43,400
lying in the crack, between this B flat

00:40:43,500 --> 00:40:48,400
and this A; it's one of those blue notes.

00:40:52,000 --> 00:40:59,400
And that blue note can be construed by the human ear as either the higher version of the note -- B flat;

00:40:59,500 --> 00:41:01,400
or the lower version A.

00:41:01,500 --> 00:41:08,400
In either case it requires a little push up or down to be accommodated on the piano.

00:41:08,500 --> 00:41:11,000
But whichever way we construe it, it becomes our newest overtone.

00:41:11,010 --> 00:41:16,000
So we are now equipped with four different overtones: the C

00:41:16,010 --> 00:41:18,000
plus the G plus the E

00:41:18,050 --> 00:41:22,000
plus that blue note, a dubious A.

00:41:22,050 --> 00:41:25,000
Or if we rearrange them in scale order,

00:41:25,100 --> 00:41:30,000
C-E-G and sort of A,

00:41:30,100 --> 00:41:36,000
and here we hear a real musical linguistic universal,

00:41:36,300 --> 00:41:41,000
because now we can understand and explain that famous worldwide teasing chat:

00:41:41,300 --> 00:41:45,000
Oly Oly Anfrey;

00:41:45,300 --> 00:41:50,000
because all it is is a constellation of those first four different overtones,

00:41:50,300 --> 00:41:55,000
with the tonic omitted, or rather implied.

00:41:55,100 --> 00:41:57,000
You see this tonic C,

00:41:57,300 --> 00:42:01,000
which is the same note as the fundamental C

00:42:01,300 --> 00:42:06,000
is heard in the mind's ear, and only the three new overtones are sound.

00:42:06,300 --> 00:42:14,300
And so these three universal notes are handed us by nature on a silver platter.

00:42:14,600 --> 00:42:17,300
But why are they in this different order?

00:42:18,000 --> 00:42:23,300
Because that's the very order in which they appear in the harmonic series.

00:42:23,600 --> 00:42:30,800
G-E and sort of A and Q-E-D

00:42:31,600 --> 00:42:34,300
Now this is a substantive universal,

00:42:34,600 --> 00:42:37,300
the sort of thing linguists hunger for,

00:42:37,600 --> 00:42:40,300
but the likeness of which are simply unavailable to them.

00:42:40,600 --> 00:42:43,000
Indeed, as we ascend further in our harmonic series,

00:42:43,003 --> 00:42:48,000
more and more fascinating and incontrovertible universals keep appearing.

00:42:48,200 --> 00:42:54,300
For instance this next new overtone is this one, that is the new overtone,

00:42:54,500 --> 00:42:56,300
is this one D.

00:42:56,500 --> 00:43:00,300
So now we have five different tones to play with,

00:43:03,500 --> 00:43:06,300
which we again put into scale order.

00:43:08,500 --> 00:43:15,300
And presto a new universal is given us the 5 note or pentatonic scale.

00:43:16,500 --> 00:43:22,000
And because of that dubious last note, the scale can take either of two forms.

00:43:22,005 --> 00:43:27,500
One culminating in B flat, and the other culminating in A.

00:43:27,700 --> 00:43:31,200
Let's opt to the second of these, the lower one,

00:43:31,300 --> 00:43:33,200
which is by far the most common of the two.

00:43:36,000 --> 00:43:40,200
This is humanity's favourite pentatonic scale, and by the way,

00:43:40,400 --> 00:43:46,200
this is the scale you can find so easily on your own piano by playing only the black notes.

00:43:48,000 --> 00:43:52,200,
In fact, the universality of this scale is so well-known,

00:43:52,300 --> 00:43:56,200
that I'm sure you can give me examples of it from all corners of the earth:

00:43:56,300 --> 00:44:03,200
from Scotland -- pure pentatonic;

00:44:03,300 --> 00:44:20,200
or from China; or from Africa

00:44:21,300 --> 00:44:27,200
and from the American-Indian cultures, and from Eastern Indian cultures and from central and south Amerima,

00:44:27,300 --> 00:44:30,200
and Australia and Finland and

00:44:30,300 --> 00:44:33,200
Well, that's a true musical linguistic universal.

00:44:33,300 --> 00:44:37,200
But let's be careful about making linguistic analogies.

00:44:37,300 --> 00:44:41,200
We could conceivably equate a fundamental tone, such as this C,

00:44:42,300 --> 00:44:46,200
with the basic morpheme "ma", which we discovered before

00:44:46,300 --> 00:44:52,200
and then extend the parallel equating the overtones of that fundamental C

00:44:52,300 --> 00:44:57,200
with a set of words evolving from that "ma" syllable.

00:44:57,300 --> 00:45:00,200
Maybe! It's all still speculation.

00:45:00,300 --> 00:45:03,000
But what appears to be much more convincing

00:45:03,020 --> 00:45:07,200
is the analogy between Chomtsky's innate grammatical competence

00:45:07,300 --> 00:45:14,200
and the innate musical grammatical competence, which we may all possess universally;

00:45:14,230 --> 00:45:20,200
that is our in-built capacity to construe those naturally serialised overtones

00:45:20,230 --> 00:45:23,200
and to contrue them in different ways.

00:45:23,300 --> 00:45:30,200
Just as the various cultures of the world may have construed basic monogenetic materials

00:45:30,230 --> 00:45:35,200
and constructed out of them thousands of particular grammars or languages,

00:45:35,230 --> 00:45:37,200
all different from one another.

00:45:37,230 --> 00:45:45,200
Analagously, varied human cultures can construe this pentatonic scale in different ways,

00:45:45,300 --> 00:45:52,200
depending for example on which of the five notes is taken to be the tonal center.

00:45:52,300 --> 00:45:54,200
For example this one:

00:45:56,300 --> 00:45:58,200
that's one way.

00:45:58,300 --> 00:46:00,200
Or this one:

00:46:02,000 --> 00:46:07,200
you see how it makes the whole different pentatonic but the same five notes.

00:46:07,300 --> 00:46:11,200
Or this one, same five notes again but a different scale.

00:46:15,000 --> 00:46:18,200
And there is always that blue notes to be considered.

00:46:18,400 --> 00:46:25,200
If the ear construes it as the upper B flat instead of the lower A,

00:46:25,400 --> 00:46:28,200
it will give us a whole other pentatonic scale,

00:46:30,400 --> 00:46:34,200
which produces some beautiful African music.

00:46:34,400 --> 00:46:38,000
And there are even much more complix processes which we won't go into,

00:46:38,020 --> 00:46:44,200
but which account for the existence of the highly differentiated Japanese pentatonic scale.

00:46:48,000 --> 00:46:52,200
Does that sound familiar?

00:46:52,300 --> 00:46:56,200
Or the unique pentatonic of the Balinese music.

00:47:02,000 --> 00:47:08,200
But enough of pentatonics. I think we have seen enough of the way the harmonic series uprates,

00:47:08,400 --> 00:47:13,200
to recognise the fact that as we ascend the series,

00:47:13,400 --> 00:47:17,200
always finding new tones to be added (Oops..).

00:47:17,400 --> 00:47:21,200
There we are, to be added to our collection,

00:47:21,400 --> 00:47:28,200
we can eventually account for six and seven notes scales including Greek modes and church modes,

00:47:28,400 --> 00:47:34,200
and the diatonic scales both major and minor, and eventually all twelve tones

00:47:34,230 --> 00:47:38,200
of our so-called chromatic scale;

00:47:40,400 --> 00:47:44,200
which is of course due to the merit of tempering,

00:47:45,400 --> 00:47:48,200
we get those twelve equidistant tones.

00:47:48,400 --> 00:47:55,200
And you may well ask why just twelve tones. Patience, you'll find out in a minute.

00:47:55,400 --> 00:47:59,200
But even these twelve tones don't exauhst the potential of the harmonic series;

00:47:59,400 --> 00:48:03,200
the upper reaches of the seires contintue

00:48:03,240 --> 00:48:09,200
to furnish us with intervals even smaller than the half tones that make up our chromatic scale.

00:48:11,500 --> 00:48:17,200
Intervals such as quarter tones, or even thirds and fifths of tones,

00:48:17,250 --> 00:48:21,200
all of which are still inhabit the areas of experimentation,

00:48:21,300 --> 00:48:23,200
like electronic research;

00:48:23,300 --> 00:48:29,200
to say nothing of microtones, which are such an essential part of so much oriental music.

00:48:29,300 --> 00:48:32,200
But the overwriting fact that emerges from all this

00:48:32,300 --> 00:48:38,200
is that all music, whether pop, folk, symphonic

00:48:38,230 --> 00:48:45,200
modal, tonal, atonal, poly-tonal, micro-tonal, well-tempered or ill-tempered,

00:48:45,300 --> 00:48:50,200
music from the distant past or the imminent future, all of it

00:48:50,300 --> 00:48:56,200
has a common origin in the universal phenomenon of the harmonic serials.

00:48:56,300 --> 00:48:59,200
And that is our case for musical monogenesis.

00:48:59,300 --> 00:49:04,200
But is it necessarily a case for music universality? Think!

00:49:04,300 --> 00:49:10,200
What about those Hindu Ragas so many people find difficult to comprehend.

00:49:10,300 --> 00:49:12,200
Well I suggest a simple answer.

00:49:12,300 --> 00:49:20,200
In the light of our linguistic analogies, just as the grammars of human languages,

00:49:20,300 --> 00:49:23,200
even mutually unintelligible ones,

00:49:23,300 --> 00:49:27,200
may have sprung from the same monogenetic sources,

00:49:27,300 --> 00:49:33,200
so in the same way, highly varied musical tongues,

00:49:33,300 --> 00:49:39,200
which are also strangers to one another, can be said to have developed out of their common origins.

00:49:39,300 --> 00:49:42,200
In purely phonological terms,

00:49:42,300 --> 00:49:46,200
these tongues are tonal languages that have developed out of a universal,

00:49:46,300 --> 00:49:50,200
naturally ordered, tonal structure.

00:49:51,000 --> 00:49:55,200
Now I trust you realise that all of this has been enormously compressed

00:49:55,205 --> 00:50:00,200
and undocumented by historical musical examples, because that will take all night;

00:50:00,300 --> 00:50:06,200
but this is not a linguistics course; nor is it a history of music course.

00:50:06,300 --> 00:50:10,200
What we are trying for is a very high overview

00:50:10,300 --> 00:50:16,200
of musical development in terms of a vocabulary constantly being enriched,

00:50:16,300 --> 00:50:20,200
by more and more remote and chromatic overtones.

00:50:20,300 --> 00:50:28,200
It's as if we can see the whole of music developing from prehistory to the present in two minutes.

00:50:28,300 --> 00:50:36,200
Let's again pretend we're homonids, and that the smash hit moment is, let's say Fair Harvard.

00:50:36,300 --> 00:50:41,200
Here we are, in our homonid hut crooning,

00:50:45,300 --> 00:50:52,200
and now maybe our wives and maybe our pre-pubescence sons join in,

00:50:52,300 --> 00:50:56,200
and automatically, we are singing not in unison, but in octives,

00:50:56,230 --> 00:51:00,200
since men's and women's voices are naturally an octive apart.

00:51:05,300 --> 00:51:11,200
Now that octive interval, I wish I could sing an octive so I can really show you what I mean.

00:51:11,300 --> 00:51:16,200
But that octive interval happens to be the first interval of the harmonic series as you remember, right?

00:51:16,300 --> 00:51:24,200
OK. Now centuries passed and the next interval of the harmonic series is assimilated by humanity,

00:51:24,300 --> 00:51:29,200
namely the fifth. And now we can be singing this.

00:51:35,300 --> 00:51:40,200
Now of course this little change brings us forward a mere ten million years,

00:51:40,300 --> 00:51:46,200
into the tenth century AD, and into a fairly sophisticated musical culture.

00:51:46,300 --> 00:51:50,200
But now we admit the next interval of the series, the fourth;

00:51:50,300 --> 00:51:57,200
and now we can mix intervals of the octive and the fifth and the fourth.

00:52:05,300 --> 00:52:08,200
Now that's beginning to sound like polyphony.

00:52:08,300 --> 00:52:14,200
And again comes a great leap, as music absorbs the next overtone, the third.

00:52:14,300 --> 00:52:16,200
And just listen to the difference.

00:52:20,300 --> 00:52:27,200
It's a whole new music, richer, mellower, with a new colouristic warmth.

00:52:27,300 --> 00:52:30,200
And as we know, this new interval of the third,

00:52:30,300 --> 00:52:34,200
bacause I like the older sound better, anyway, ah...

00:52:34,300 --> 00:52:39,200
As we know this new interval of the third introduces into music

00:52:39,230 --> 00:52:41,200
the phenomenon of the triad,

00:52:41,230 --> 00:52:47,200
so that now Fair Harvard can begin to sound more like its Victorian self.

00:52:50,300 --> 00:52:56,200
And so there was born, what we now call, tonal music;

00:52:56,300 --> 00:53:03,200
a stable tonal language, firmly rooted in the basic notes of the harmonic series:

00:53:03,300 --> 00:53:07,200
The fundamental and its first different overtone, the fifth;

00:53:07,300 --> 00:53:13,200
now and for evermore to be known as the tonic and the dominant.

00:53:13,300 --> 00:53:16,200
And that fifth interval really does dominate,

00:53:16,300 --> 00:53:20,200
because once this tonic-dominant relationship is established,

00:53:20,300 --> 00:53:22,200
it's a field day for composers.

00:53:22,300 --> 00:53:26,200
There can be now a fifth of fifth of fifth of fifth;

00:53:26,300 --> 00:53:33,200
each one of them, a new tonic producing a new dominant, a whole circle of fifths;

00:53:33,300 --> 00:53:38,200
twelve of them in fact; always winding up with the starting tone;

00:53:38,300 --> 00:53:41,200
whether proceeding upwards, let's say from the low C,

00:53:41,300 --> 00:53:48,200
G, D, A, E, B, F#, C#, G#, Eb, Bb, F, C.

00:53:48,300 --> 00:53:50,200
That's again C,  believe it or not that?

00:53:52,300 --> 00:53:54,200
Or proceeding downwards, starting from that

00:53:54,300 --> 00:54:03,200
C, F, Bb, Eb, Ab, Db, Gb, B, E, A, D, G, C

00:54:03,300 --> 00:54:09,200
back to C, that's the circle of twelve fifths, and that's the answer I promised you;

00:54:09,300 --> 00:54:13,200
that's how we got our twelve different tones of our chromatic scale.

00:54:13,300 --> 00:54:17,200
Because if you take all those twelve of the circle of fifths,

00:54:17,300 --> 00:54:21,200
and put them together in scale order, you'll get this.

00:54:23,300 --> 00:54:28,200
And what's more those twelve notes generate a circle of twelve different keys,

00:54:28,300 --> 00:54:32,200
through which, thanks to the perfecting of the tempered system,

00:54:32,300 --> 00:54:39,200
composers can now go free willing at their own chromatic pleasure.

00:54:43,300 --> 00:54:48,200
And this means ultimately Fear Harvard can sound like this.

00:54:55,300 --> 00:55:03,200
That's chromatic porrige; and in our own century it's going to become goulash.

00:55:03,300 --> 00:55:09,200
How does music contain this loose runny chromaticism?

00:55:09,300 --> 00:55:13,200
By the basic principle of diatonicism;

00:55:13,300 --> 00:55:18,200
that stable relationship of tonics, and dominants,

00:55:18,300 --> 00:55:26,200
sub-dominants, and super-tonics and new dominants and new tonics,

00:55:26,300 --> 00:55:31,200
and we can now modulate as freely as we want, as chromatically as we want,

00:55:31,300 --> 00:55:35,200
and still have complete tonal control.

00:55:35,300 --> 00:55:46,200
This great system of tonal controls was perfected and codified by Bach, J.S.Bach,

00:55:46,300 --> 00:55:52,200
whose genius was to balance so delicately and so justly

00:55:52,300 --> 00:55:56,200
these two forces of chromaticism and diatonicism,

00:55:56,300 --> 00:56:01,200
forces that were equally powerful and presumably contradictory in nature.

00:56:01,300 --> 00:56:04,200
And this point of delicate balance

00:56:04,300 --> 00:56:09,200
is like the still center in the stormy flux of musical history.

00:56:09,300 --> 00:56:12,200
A condition of such stability

00:56:12,300 --> 00:56:16,200
that was able to continue without remarkable changes for almost a century;

00:56:16,300 --> 00:56:22,200
and this roughly a hundred years became a golden age.

00:56:22,300 --> 00:56:28,200
This is not to say that there weren't drastic changes in style and form during those hundrend years.

00:56:28,300 --> 00:56:33,200
It's after all this golden age saw emergence of a whole new Rococo style;

00:56:33,300 --> 00:56:37,200
to say nothing of the phenomenal rise of sonata form

00:56:37,230 --> 00:56:45,200
and the hands of such giants as C.P.E.Bach and Haydn and Mozart and Beethoven himself.

00:56:45,300 --> 00:56:49,200
But these changes are syntactic and semantic changes,

00:56:49,230 --> 00:56:53,200
which will be examining and enjoying in future lectures.

00:56:53,300 --> 00:56:57,200
Right now, we are limiting our investigation to phonology;

00:56:57,300 --> 00:57:01,200
and in these terms, we can see the peak attained by Bach,

00:57:01,300 --> 00:57:08,200
continuing as a kind of a plateau, level and lofty right into the music of Beethoven.

00:57:08,300 --> 00:57:15,200
Now at this point, I'd like to invite you to listen with me to one of the supreme examples of this golden age:

00:57:15,300 --> 00:57:22,200
Mozart's G minor symphony, a work of utmost passion utterly controlled

00:57:22,300 --> 00:57:26,200
and of free chromaticism elegantly contained.

00:57:26,300 --> 00:57:33,200
I'll try to prepare you a bit somewhat with a few illustrations of this control and containment,

00:57:33,300 --> 00:57:39,200
so that you can hear the symphony, hopefully with fresh phonological ears.

00:57:39,300 --> 00:57:46,200
And remember what we are looking for is the wonderfully creative way in which chromatic flexibility

00:57:46,300 --> 00:57:52,200
can be systematically contained within the framework of tonic-dominant relationships.

00:57:52,300 --> 00:57:56,200
It's a curious thing and a crucial one,

00:57:56,300 --> 00:58:00,200
that through this perfect combination of opposites,

00:58:00,300 --> 00:58:08,200
chromaticism and diatonicism, there is distiled the essence of ambiguity of all things.

00:58:08,300 --> 00:58:11,200
This word "ambiguity" may seem to be the most unlikely word

00:58:11,300 --> 00:58:15,200
to use in speaking of a golden age composer like Mozart,

00:58:15,300 --> 00:58:18,200
a master of clarity and precision.

00:58:18,300 --> 00:58:24,200
But ambiguity has always inhabited musical art, indeed all the arts;

00:58:24,300 --> 00:58:28,200
because it is one of art's most potent aesthetic functions.

00:58:28,300 --> 00:58:34,200
The more ambiguous, the more expressive, up to a certain point, of course there is a limit,

00:58:34,300 --> 00:58:37,200
which we are going to run into in the course of these lectures.

00:58:37,300 --> 00:58:42,200
We are going to run into a state of such increased ambiguity

00:58:42,300 --> 00:58:46,200
that problems of musical clarity are bound to arise;

00:58:46,230 --> 00:58:52,200
and that's where we'll be confronted head on by Ive's unanswered question: whither.

00:58:52,300 --> 00:58:55,800
Meanwhile, we are still in the golden age

00:58:56,000 --> 00:59:01,200
with ambiguity classically contained in the Augusten balances and proportions

00:59:01,300 --> 00:59:04,200
in here into this Mozart's symphony.

00:59:04,300 --> 00:59:06,200
Let's look at it very briefly.

00:59:06,300 --> 00:59:11,200
You all remember the opening in first movement.

00:59:20,300 --> 00:59:25,200
This whole section moves quite easily and diatonically from its G minor

00:59:25,300 --> 00:59:31,200
tonic, to its first kins, which is naturally enough on the dominant.

00:59:35,300 --> 00:59:38,200
And just as easily slipping back into the tonic.

00:59:42,300 --> 00:59:44,200
Back we are.

00:59:45,000 --> 00:59:48,200
Now, of course you remember that this tonic-dominant relationship

00:59:48,205 --> 00:59:51,200
arises from the adjacency of the fundamental tone,

00:59:51,300 --> 00:59:55,200
in this case this G, with its first overtone that basic interval of the fifth.

00:59:55,300 --> 01:00:00,200
And from there the music proceeds by a circle of fifths,

01:00:00,300 --> 01:00:03,200
downward circle of fifths;

01:00:03,300 --> 01:00:10,200
to it's relative major Bb, which is exactly where it's supposed to be

01:00:10,300 --> 01:00:13,200
for the appearence of the second thematic section.

01:00:18,300 --> 01:00:22,200
But notice that Mozart's theme has already chromatically formed;

01:00:24,000 --> 01:00:26,200
and it gets more so as it goes on;

01:00:28,300 --> 01:00:31,200
and even more so as it repeats.

01:00:34,300 --> 01:00:39,200
What's this? A whole new key, Ab major;

01:00:39,300 --> 01:00:43,200
a sudden new key, unrelated to either Bb or G minor.

01:00:43,300 --> 01:00:48,200
How did we get here? By the well-known circle of fifths.

01:00:48,300 --> 01:00:58,200
Did you hear those stable consecutive fifths striding inexorably from domanmints to tonic in the base.

01:01:02,300 --> 01:01:06,200
Dominant-tonic, Dominant-tonic, Dominant-tonic.

01:01:06,300 --> 01:01:14,200
While above the melodical line descends by chromatic half steps into the nether regions of Ab major.

01:01:14,300 --> 01:01:19,200
There's that the classical balance we are talking about: chromatic wandering on the top,

01:01:21,000 --> 01:01:25,200
but firmly supported by the tonic-dominant structure underneath.

01:01:28,300 --> 01:01:33,200
And you see now what I meant by the beauty of ambiguity,

01:01:33,300 --> 01:01:40,200
it is combination of those two contradictory forces: chromaticism and diatonicism,

01:01:40,300 --> 01:01:44,200
uprating at the same time, that makes this passage so expressive.

01:01:48,300 --> 01:01:51,200
So we are in the midst of chromatic adventure, right?

01:01:51,220 --> 01:01:55,200
How do we get out of this strange Ab territory.

01:01:55,300 --> 01:02:00,200
By a simple chromatic shift like side-slipping on skis.

01:02:04,300 --> 01:02:08,200
And there we are back safely in Bb major where we belong.

01:02:08,300 --> 01:02:14,000
Now, if you could follow that, you could follow any number of similar adventures.

01:02:14,001 --> 01:02:17,200
For instance, the way Mozart starts his development section.

01:02:17,300 --> 01:02:20,200
It's established as firmly in Bb major.

01:02:21,300 --> 01:02:23,200
But no!

01:02:25,300 --> 01:02:28,200
Off he goes on another chromatic adventure,

01:02:32,300 --> 01:02:36,200
which lands us in the impossible key of F# minor.

01:02:36,300 --> 01:02:40,200
Now this was done by absolute whim arbitrarily;

01:02:40,300 --> 01:02:43,200
it's a bit of chromatic acrobatics if you will,

01:02:43,203 --> 01:02:46,200
startling passage with development section,

01:02:46,300 --> 01:02:51,200
which is what the development section should be, a startling new looks at old material.

01:02:51,300 --> 01:02:56,200
But eventually he must get us back to a recapitulation in G minor,

01:02:56,300 --> 01:02:58,200
the original home soil.

01:02:58,300 --> 01:03:02,200
And he is completely free to make this journey as chromatically as he wishes,

01:03:02,220 --> 01:03:06,200
his fantacy is totally released; it's a development section.

01:03:06,300 --> 01:03:08,200
Freewheeling to act!

01:03:08,300 --> 01:03:15,200
But even here, the basic diatonic laws contain and control that freewheeling,

01:03:15,300 --> 01:03:17,200
passion and fantacy.

01:03:17,300 --> 01:03:22,200
And all by those progressions of fifths, the dominant seeking it's tonic,

01:03:22,300 --> 01:03:26,200
and each tonic turning into a dominant seeking its tonic,

01:03:26,300 --> 01:03:30,200
and that tonic tuning into seeking its own tonic and over and over again.

01:03:30,300 --> 01:03:33,200
We are in F# minor right?

01:03:33,300 --> 01:03:36,200
Now through a sequence of such progressons,

01:03:36,220 --> 01:03:44,200
it changes that F# minor tonality from tonic function to a dominant function,

01:03:44,300 --> 01:03:47,200
which is seeking its tonic B natural,

01:03:47,300 --> 01:03:52,200
and here we are, here is that B natural.

01:03:52,300 --> 01:03:58,200
And B natural as a dominant seeking its tonic E. And so into E we go;

01:04:00,300 --> 01:04:04,200
and by the same chain of fifths, E seeks A.

01:04:06,300 --> 01:04:09,200
That's A, then A seeks D.

01:04:11,300 --> 01:04:17,200
D -- and so on through the circle until we finally lead back home to G minor.

01:04:17,300 --> 01:04:23,200
But even this leaning to the home key is chromatically written,

01:04:23,300 --> 01:04:26,200
firmly held in place of course, by the dominant pedal.

01:04:27,300 --> 01:04:31,200
Listen to this creepy crawly chromaticism.

01:04:44,300 --> 01:04:52,200
We are back to our old so gratifying and welcome recapitulation in G minor.

01:04:52,300 --> 01:04:59,200
Now I must point out that these adventures are much more complex and subtle than I made them sound;

01:04:59,300 --> 01:05:02,200
the procedure is not always exactly by fifths;

01:05:02,300 --> 01:05:05,200
there are twists and turns which will take

01:05:05,230 --> 01:05:09,200
hours to describe acurately even to a classroom of Harvard music students.

01:05:09,300 --> 01:05:16,200
The best I can do is to give you some insight into this marvel of ambiguity.

01:05:16,300 --> 01:05:20,100
The diatonic containment of chromaticism,

01:05:20,200 --> 01:05:24,200
so that when you hear, for instance, this second movement,

01:05:24,300 --> 01:05:27,200
this extraordinary chromatic passage,

01:05:31,300 --> 01:05:36,200
you can also be aware of the strong diatonic underpinnings:

01:05:36,300 --> 01:05:41,200
those fifths again striding inexorably from tonic to dominant.

01:05:45,300 --> 01:05:47,200
See if you can hear them.

01:05:53,300 --> 01:05:59,200
Even in the third movement, the minuet, which is extremely diatonic; it's hardly chromatic at all,

01:06:03,300 --> 01:06:09,200
Mozart can't resist just before the end one of his charming chromatic excursions.

01:06:11,300 --> 01:06:17,200
But instantly it all writes itself in the classical tonic-dominant cadence.

01:06:22,300 --> 01:06:26,200
But the most breath-taking chromatic trip of all occurs in the final movement,

01:06:26,300 --> 01:06:28,200
which begins as you remember

01:06:31,300 --> 01:06:36,200
Innocent enough and tonally not too eventful throughout the whole exposition.

01:06:36,300 --> 01:06:42,200
But then again comes the development section, and all hell breaks loose.

01:06:48,300 --> 01:06:53,200
Do you realise that wild and tonal sonic passage

01:06:53,300 --> 01:06:59,200
contains every one of the twelve chromatic tones except the tonic G.

01:06:59,300 --> 01:07:05,200
What an inspired idea! All the notes except the tonic.

01:07:09,300 --> 01:07:15,200
It could easily pass for 20th century's music if we didn't already know that it was Mozart.

01:07:15,300 --> 01:07:21,200
But event that explosion of chromaticism is explainable in terms of the circle of fifths.

01:07:21,203 --> 01:07:23,200
Not that I dream of burdening you with it.

01:07:23,300 --> 01:07:28,200
But take my words for it that outburst of chromatic rage

01:07:28,300 --> 01:07:33,200
is classically contained and so is the climax of this development section,

01:07:33,300 --> 01:07:40,200
which finds itself suddenly in the key of, it's not so sudden, in the key of C# minor.

01:07:43,300 --> 01:07:48,200
C# minor which is as far away as you can get from the home key of G minor,

01:07:48,300 --> 01:07:51,200
sounds pretty remote, doesn't it?

01:07:53,300 --> 01:07:58,200
And again believe me all these phonological arrivals and departures,

01:07:58,300 --> 01:08:02,200
to and from the most distantly remote areas,

01:08:02,300 --> 01:08:08,200
operating in the smoothest, most Mozartian way under perfect diatonic control.

01:08:08,300 --> 01:08:11,200
Well, what is all this add up to?

01:08:11,300 --> 01:08:15,200
Let's find out by hearing the whole work,

01:08:15,300 --> 01:08:20,200
as performed on film by the Boston symphony orchestra.

01:08:20,300 --> 01:08:27,200
And I hope we will be listening to it with fresh phonological ears.

01:39:58,300 --> 01:40:00,200
What a piece!

01:40:00,300 --> 01:40:07,200
Now last night, at the first presentation of this lecture, the Harvard's Great theatre,

01:40:08,300 --> 01:40:15,200
this performance of Mozart's symphony was interrupted in the middle of first movement by a bomb scare.

01:40:16,300 --> 01:40:20,200
And we all had to go out into the street;

01:40:20,300 --> 01:40:24,200
nobody knowing whether we were going to come back and resume or not;

01:40:25,300 --> 01:40:28,200
and wait for almost an hour,

01:40:28,300 --> 01:40:34,200
until we had word that the police cleared the whole theatre.

01:40:35,300 --> 01:40:39,200
And during that wait,

01:40:39,300 --> 01:40:43,200
I must say that I was sick at heart and

01:40:43,300 --> 01:40:49,200
overcome by despair because why had I been

01:40:50,300 --> 01:40:58,200
talking my guts out for an hour and a half on human brotherhood and universality

01:40:58,300 --> 01:41:09,200
only to have this kind of despicable disproof of human brotherhood thrown in our faces.

01:41:10,300 --> 01:41:16,200
And when I came back, and we all came back, and so many of the audiences did come back.

01:41:16,300 --> 01:41:18,200
My amazement.

01:41:19,000 --> 01:41:25,200
And listen from the beginning again, through to the end of this symphony.

01:41:25,300 --> 01:41:30,200
I must say that my faith was restored, and doubled;

01:41:30,300 --> 01:41:35,200
not only by this incredible piece of music,

01:41:35,300 --> 01:41:42,200
which I guess if one have to point to a work that symbolised in itself the

01:41:42,300 --> 01:41:49,200
essence of the whole fustian experience of man,

01:41:49,300 --> 01:41:53,200
since the Renaissance; this will be it.

01:41:55,300 --> 01:42:01,200
But also because of the number of the audience that waited it out,

01:42:01,300 --> 01:42:06,200
and came back, and listened to it. Terribly moved.

01:42:07,300 --> 01:42:13,200
Of course, I wouldn't have been so upset if the interruption had come during my talk,

01:42:13,205 --> 01:42:19,200
but interrupt Mozart, which were that extraordinary

01:42:19,300 --> 01:42:25,200
wholeness and continuity, that entity which is this work,

01:42:26,300 --> 01:42:29,200
was the greatest insult of all.

01:42:30,300 --> 01:42:36,200
But as I say my faith was restored, just to hear it;

01:42:36,300 --> 01:42:42,200
and just to hear it with those people, and through them.

01:42:43,300 --> 01:42:50,200
So I feel even more confident over what I was trying to say in the beginning

01:42:50,300 --> 01:42:52,200
than I had when wrote it.

01:42:54,300 --> 01:43:01,200
Just a short word now about our subject next time, which will be syntax.

01:43:01,300 --> 01:43:06,200
If you remember the second of the three linguistic departments.

01:43:07,300 --> 01:43:10,200
Musical and linguistic syntax,

01:43:11,300 --> 01:43:15,200
in which we will be examining the actual formations

01:43:15,210 --> 01:43:19,200
of these phonological elements we've been discussing this time.

01:43:19,300 --> 01:43:23,200
And then we'll be ready to understand the semantic problems

01:43:23,300 --> 01:43:26,200
of music from Mozart to the present.

01:43:26,300 --> 01:43:35,200
And hopefully come closer and closer to understanding, and maybe even answering Ive's unanswered question.

01:43:35,300 --> 01:43:37,200
Thank you.
